---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="PrecisionMemBench — LLM Memory Retrieval Benchmark | Tenure"
  description="89-case benchmark measuring retrieval precision independently of generative models. Tenure: 1.0 precision, 89/89 passes. Mem0, Zep, Hindsight: 0 active retrieval passes. Published on arXiv."
>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Dataset",
  "name": "PrecisionMemBench",
  "description": "An 89-case benchmark measuring LLM memory retrieval precision independently of generative models. Covers alias resolution, scope disambiguation, supersession chain exclusion, fuzzy matching, cross-user isolation, session-level noise isolation, and multi-turn topic drift.",
  "url": "https://tenureai.dev/benchmark",
  "sameAs": [
    "https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.11325",
    "https://github.com/tenurehq/precisionMemBench",
    "https://huggingface.co/spaces/tenurehq/precisionmembench"
  ],
  "license": "https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT",
  "creator": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Jeffrey Flynt",
    "email": "jeffrey.flynt@utexas.edu"
  },
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Tenure",
    "url": "https://tenureai.dev"
  },
  "datePublished": "2026-05-27",
  "keywords": ["LLM memory", "retrieval precision", "AI memory benchmark", "RAG evaluation", "BM25", "vector search"],
  "measurementTechnique": "Retrieval precision and recall evaluated independently of generative models using mustExclude and shouldOnlyInclude assertions",
  "variableMeasured": ["retrieval precision", "retrieval recall", "drift score", "retrieval latency", "ingestion latency"]
}
</script>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "ScholarlyArticle",
  "headline": "Structured Belief State and the First Precision-Aware Benchmark for LLM Memory Retrieval",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Jeffrey Flynt",
    "affiliation": "Independent Researcher"
  },
  "datePublished": "2026-05-27",
  "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.11325",
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "arXiv"
  },
  "description": "We present PrecisionMemBench, an 89-case benchmark measuring retrieval precision independently of generative models, and Tenure, a local-first structured belief store achieving 1.0 precision and 89/89 benchmark passes.",
  "about": {
    "@type": "Dataset",
    "name": "PrecisionMemBench",
    "url": "https://tenureai.dev/benchmark"
  }
}
</script>

<section id="bench-hero" class="bench-hero">
  <div class="container" style="text-align:center;">
    <span class="label">PrecisionMemBench</span>
    <h1>The benchmark that measures<br/>what memory tools actually do.</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">
      Every existing benchmark measures whether the model answered correctly.<br/>
      This one measures whether the memory system <em>retrieved</em> correctly.<br/>
      Those are not the same question.
    </p>

    <div class="bench-hero-stats">
      <div class="bench-hero-stat">
        <span class="bench-hero-value good">89</span>
        <span class="bench-hero-label">Total cases</span>
      </div>
      <div class="bench-hero-stat-div"></div>
      <div class="bench-hero-stat">
        <span class="bench-hero-value good">5</span>
        <span class="bench-hero-label">Systems evaluated</span>
      </div>
      <div class="bench-hero-stat-div"></div>
      <div class="bench-hero-stat">
        <span class="bench-hero-value good">0</span>
        <span class="bench-hero-label">Active retrieval passes<br/><span style="font-size:0.7rem;font-weight:400;">for every competitor</span></span>
      </div>
      <div class="bench-hero-stat-div"></div>
      <div class="bench-hero-stat">
        <span class="bench-hero-value good">1.0</span>
        <span class="bench-hero-label">Tenure precision</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bench-cta-row">
      <a href="https://github.com/tenurehq/precisionMemBench" class="btn-primary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Run it yourself →
      </a>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.11325" class="btn-secondary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Read the paper
      </a>
      <a href="https://huggingface.co/spaces/tenurehq/precisionmembench" class="btn-secondary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        HuggingFace leaderboard
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="bench-section" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="label">The problem</span>
    <h2>Why existing benchmarks are measuring the wrong thing</h2>
    <p>LoCoMo, LongMemEval, and every benchmark built on top of them measure answer quality through a generative judge. This design cannot distinguish a memory system that retrieves one correct belief from one that retrieves its entire store.</p>

    <div class="gap-grid">
      <div class="gap-card gap-card-bad">
        <div class="gap-card-header">
          <span class="gap-icon">✗</span>
          <h3>Answer-quality benchmarks</h3>
        </div>
        <p>Retrieve everything. Route through a model. Score on F1. A system with 0.05 retrieval precision looks "competitive" because the downstream model compensates for the noise.</p>
        <div class="gap-terminal">
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-dim">-- retrieve everything</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-cmd">SELECT * FROM beliefs</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-dim">-- hope the model sorts it out</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-dim">-- 18 results injected</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span style="color:var(--red);">-- precision: 0.05</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="gap-card gap-card-good">
        <div class="gap-card-header">
          <span class="gap-icon good">✓</span>
          <h3>PrecisionMemBench</h3>
        </div>
        <p>Assert against retrieved beliefs directly. No generative model in the evaluation loop. <code>mustExclude</code> and <code>shouldOnlyInclude</code> make noise a hard failure.</p>
        <div class="gap-terminal">
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-dim">-- query at the source</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-cmd">SELECT * FROM beliefs</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-cmd">WHERE scope = 'project:api'</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-cmd">AND alias_match('redis')</span></div>
          <div class="gap-terminal-line"><span class="t-ok">-- 1 result. precision: 1.0</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="compare-verdict" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      <p>Strip the generative model out and route retrieved context to a classifier, rules engine, or structured pipeline: current retrieval implementations fail immediately. The generative model was never a neutral consumer — it was load-bearing infrastructure compensating for retrieval noise.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

